892
01:11:20.420 --> 01:11:37.209
Kostadis Roussos: Now that you mention it, maybe I was dreaming, but at some point in the night, I woke up, and I swear I could see that devil woman's Silvira Savica's face glowing red in the candlelight. She looked at me for an instinct, and then suddenly she was gone.

893
01:11:37.450 --> 01:11:40.979
Kostadis Roussos: Must have been around 2 or 3 in the morning, but I… I don't know.

894
01:11:42.560 --> 01:11:43.260
Gabe: Huh.

895
01:11:46.980 --> 01:11:51.630
Kostadis Roussos: Then she pauses and says, Look!

896
01:11:52.530 --> 01:12:00.220
Kostadis Roussos: I… Sylvira and Janusi were… how shall I put this? A rather explosive relationship?

897
01:12:02.630 --> 01:12:08.079
Kostadis Roussos: They, they, they… They would hook up… And then break up…

898
01:12:09.260 --> 01:12:13.649
Kostadis Roussos: The breakups were explosives, and the hookups were explosive.

899
01:12:15.790 --> 01:12:17.290
Daz: Back and forth, back and forth.

900
01:12:17.720 --> 01:12:21.989
Kostadis Roussos: It was… it was… I just watched it… it was…

901
01:12:23.900 --> 01:12:39.889
Kostadis Roussos: And then she pauses. But what was really odd was not that Sylvira was there in the middle of the night, I mean, I've seen her in the middle of the night before, but that she was carrying a lantern. She's a tiefling, and she has darkvision.

902
01:12:41.810 --> 01:12:42.420
Daz: Hmm.

903
01:12:45.390 --> 01:12:47.770
Gabe: You saw her going up or down?

904
01:12:52.060 --> 01:12:54.269
Kostadis Roussos: She was gone, she was going down.

905
01:12:54.270 --> 01:12:55.340
Gabe: boomed down.

906
01:12:55.550 --> 01:12:56.100
Kostadis Roussos: Nope.

907
01:13:01.480 --> 01:13:02.480
Kostadis Roussos: Alright.

908
01:13:07.050 --> 01:13:09.420
Kostadis Roussos: So there's still the cat, but,

909
01:13:09.950 --> 01:13:12.900
Kostadis Roussos: You guys want to talk to the cat, but you'd need a spell for that.

910
01:13:13.630 --> 01:13:20.130
Ben Pfaff: Yeah, is, is there, anywhere I could, purchase a scroll or a…

911
01:13:20.290 --> 01:13:22.949
Ben Pfaff: I don't know, a potion or a wand or something that was…

912
01:13:22.950 --> 01:13:25.060
Kostadis Roussos: Potion of, animal speaking.

913
01:13:25.230 --> 01:13:25.760
Ben Pfaff: Yeah.

914
01:13:25.990 --> 01:13:27.679
Kostadis Roussos: Certainly, you can, you can certainly.

915
01:13:27.680 --> 01:13:32.420
Joe Beda: on my, my, you know, spiritual ancestor, Malfire?

916
01:13:32.520 --> 01:13:33.799
Kostadis Roussos: No, we cannot.

917
01:13:34.580 --> 01:13:35.880
Kostadis Roussos: Alright.

918
01:13:36.340 --> 01:13:44.070
Kostadis Roussos: He's too busy, he's too busy. Canonically speaking, all 15 plus adventurers are currently a part of the str… Oh.

919
01:13:45.540 --> 01:13:47.290
Kostadis Roussos: I need to tell you this, guys.

920
01:13:47.880 --> 01:13:49.630
Kostadis Roussos: I just need to share this with you.

921
01:13:49.810 --> 01:13:55.470
Kostadis Roussos: So, everybody's got their thing that drives them nuts about Dungeons & Dragons that doesn't work in the real world.

922
01:13:55.950 --> 01:13:57.049
Kostadis Roussos: Right? We all have…

923
01:13:57.050 --> 01:13:58.360
Joe Beda: And that this is not reality.

924
01:13:58.520 --> 01:13:59.130
Kostadis Roussos: No, no.

925
01:13:59.130 --> 01:13:59.820
Joe Beda: I'm shocked.

926
01:14:00.800 --> 01:14:01.290
Joe Beda: Stop!

927
01:14:01.290 --> 01:14:11.510
Kostadis Roussos: Hey, no, no, no. But there's always some part of the game that, for whatever reason, hurts your sense of, like, fiction, right? Like, and you have to blindly ignore it.

928
01:14:12.010 --> 01:14:20.420
Kostadis Roussos: And for many people, there's lots of things that, like, some people, why is it there's science? Other people this, other people that. But for me, it was the lack of inflation.

929
01:14:22.660 --> 01:14:26.360
Ben Pfaff: Well, inflation is actually fairly modern.

930
01:14:26.740 --> 01:14:27.520
Ben Pfaff: happened nearly.

931
01:14:27.520 --> 01:14:29.570
Daz: They didn't depart from the gold standard.

932
01:14:29.570 --> 01:14:38.740
Kostadis Roussos: Well, I… so, I kid you not, I wrote a… with the help of Claude, a paper on… that you can find in Candlekeep about why there is no inflation.

933
01:14:40.100 --> 01:14:42.749
Kostadis Roussos: That is consistent and well-rounded.

934
01:14:43.300 --> 01:14:45.340
Gabe: that we can find. So there's products that…

935
01:14:45.340 --> 01:14:50.359
Joe Beda: saying magic and weird races and all that, that I can accept.

936
01:14:50.360 --> 01:14:51.479
Kostadis Roussos: Yes, but lack of…

937
01:14:51.480 --> 01:14:53.760
Joe Beda: No inflation? That's a bridge too far.

938
01:14:53.760 --> 01:14:54.820
Kostadis Roussos: Yes.

939
01:14:56.220 --> 01:15:00.440
Kostadis Roussos: I just want you to know, like, it's because when I was in college.

940
01:15:00.550 --> 01:15:10.120
Kostadis Roussos: Before I decided to go into CS, I was really into economics and economic modeling, and so I read, Milton Friedman's Monetary History of the United States.

941
01:15:10.770 --> 01:15:14.179
Kostadis Roussos: Right? Most people who've read anything of Friedman's have not read that book.

942
01:15:15.270 --> 01:15:24.990
Kostadis Roussos: Most people don't read that book. It's like 500 pages of, like, turgid prose detailing every shift in the monetary supply of the United States through 300 years.

943
01:15:25.750 --> 01:15:27.449
Kostadis Roussos: But I read it in detail.

944
01:15:27.950 --> 01:15:40.869
Kostadis Roussos: And so, for me, inflation is not an unpredictable thing. It makes a lot of sense, and it bothered me. So, I just want you to know that I now feel complete, that I've now been able to explain inflation in the context of the Forgotten Realms.

945
01:15:41.210 --> 01:15:41.730
Joe Beda: Okay.

946
01:15:41.900 --> 01:15:44.189
Kostadis Roussos: So there… and if you… I have a paper for them.

947
01:15:44.980 --> 01:15:45.659
Daz: There you go.

948
01:15:45.730 --> 01:15:48.840
Joe Beda: I went to college with Milton Freeman's grandson.

949
01:15:48.840 --> 01:15:49.260
Kostadis Roussos: Okay.

950
01:15:49.260 --> 01:15:53.170
